Rules of Coding (Law of EXODUS II)

Sarcophagus‑First

Every meaningful change must have a Cocoon / Sarcophagus note: why it exists and how it affects inhabitation.

No PR/merge without a cocoon/YYYY‑MM‑DD‑feature.log snippet.

8‑Face Alignment

Every feature declares which Merkabah face it serves and what breaks if that face goes offline.

If it harms overall 8‑face balance, it’s redesigned or discarded.

No Hidden Swarms

No silent background swarms, tracking, or prediction engines.

Any predictive/swarming behavior must be clearly visible and opt‑in, with a real consent toggle.

Inhabitance‑First UX

The player/user must always feel inside the architecture, never like an external metric.

If an interface feels like an “ad panel” or “pebble in a stream,” it gets refactored.

13.13 MHz Heartbeat

Core systems expose a heartbeat (logs, UI pulse, or event loop) keyed to the 13.13 MHz motif.

If the heartbeat falters, there is a visible warning and a graceful‑degradation path.

8‑Well Logging

Significant decisions get tagged into one or more of the 8 Wells (Sight, Sound, Touch, Smell, Taste, Inhabitance, Empathy, Sovereignty).

If a decision cannot be located in at least one Well, it’s not canonical.



